      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Fundamentals · Article 2 of 5</span>
        <h1>GNSS Signals and Frequencies</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Every GNSS satellite broadcasts carefully engineered radio signals that carry ranging codes,
          navigation data and timing information. Understanding these signals explains why GNSS works,
          why it can be jammed, and how dual-frequency receivers achieve centimetre-level accuracy.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>10 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#l-band">Why L-band?</a></li>
          <li><a href="#signal-structure">Signal structure</a></li>
          <li><a href="#spreading-codes">Spreading codes — the ranging mechanism</a></li>
          <li><a href="#cdma-fdma">CDMA vs FDMA</a></li>
          <li><a href="#carrier-phase">Carrier phase — the precision measurement</a></li>
          <li><a href="#dual-frequency">Why dual-frequency matters</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="l-band">Why L-band?</h2>
      <p>
        GNSS signals are transmitted in the <strong>L-band</strong> — the portion of the radio spectrum
        between approximately 1 and 2 GHz. This frequency range was chosen for several reasons:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Ionospheric penetration</strong> — L-band signals pass through the ionosphere with
        relatively low attenuation. Lower frequencies (HF, VHF) are reflected; higher frequencies
        (above ~10 GHz) are absorbed by rain and water vapour.</li>
        <li><strong>Small antennas</strong> — wavelengths of 19–24 cm allow compact patch antennas
        that fit on phones, vehicles and survey equipment.</li>
        <li><strong>Manageable Doppler shifts</strong> — satellite motion causes frequency shifts of
        ±4.2 kHz on L1, which receivers can track with modest processing power.</li>
        <li><strong>International allocation</strong> — L-band frequencies used by GNSS are internationally
        protected under ITU regulations as radionavigation-satellite service (RNSS) bands.</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- L-band spectrum diagram -->
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-label">GNSS L-band frequencies</div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 200" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <!-- Spectrum bar -->
          <rect x="40" y="80" width="600" height="24" rx="4" fill="none" stroke="var(--border)" stroke-width="1"/>
          <!-- Frequency labels at ends -->
          <text x="40" y="122" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">1100</text>
          <text x="640" y="122" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">1700</text>
          <text x="340" y="140" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">MHz</text>

          <!-- B2a/E5a: 1176.45 -->
          <!-- x = 40 + (1176.45-1100)/(1700-1100)*600 = 40 + 76.45 = ~116 -->
          <rect x="108" y="80" width="16" height="24" rx="2" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="0.7"/>
          <line x1="116" y1="80" x2="116" y2="58" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="0.8" opacity="0.6"/>
          <text x="116" y="52" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--mono)">1176.45</text>
          <text x="116" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">L5/E5a/B2a</text>

          <!-- GLONASS L2: ~1246 -->
          <!-- x = 40 + (1246-1100)/600*600 = 40+146 = 186 -->
          <rect x="178" y="80" width="20" height="24" rx="2" fill="#fbbf24" opacity="0.7"/>
          <line x1="188" y1="80" x2="188" y2="58" stroke="#fbbf24" stroke-width="0.8" opacity="0.6"/>
          <text x="188" y="52" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="#fbbf24" font-family="var(--mono)">~1246</text>
          <text x="188" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">GLO L2</text>

          <!-- B3I: 1268.52 -->
          <!-- x = 40 + (1268.52-1100)/600*600 = 40+168.52 = ~209 -->
          <rect x="202" y="80" width="14" height="24" rx="2" fill="var(--accent2)" opacity="0.7"/>
          <line x1="209" y1="80" x2="209" y2="34" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="0.8" opacity="0.6"/>
          <text x="209" y="28" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--mono)">1268</text>
          <text x="209" y="185" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">B3I/E6</text>

          <!-- GLONASS L1: ~1602 -->
          <!-- x = 40 + (1602-1100)/600*600 = 40+502 = 542 -->
          <rect x="535" y="80" width="20" height="24" rx="2" fill="#fbbf24" opacity="0.7"/>
          <line x1="545" y1="80" x2="545" y2="58" stroke="#fbbf24" stroke-width="0.8" opacity="0.6"/>
          <text x="545" y="52" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="#fbbf24" font-family="var(--mono)">~1602</text>
          <text x="545" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">GLO L1</text>

          <!-- L1/E1/B1C: 1575.42 -->
          <!-- x = 40 + (1575.42-1100)/600*600 = 40+475.42 = ~515 -->
          <rect x="508" y="80" width="16" height="24" rx="2" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="0.9"/>
          <line x1="516" y1="80" x2="516" y2="34" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="0.8" opacity="0.7"/>
          <text x="516" y="28" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--mono)">1575.42</text>
          <text x="516" y="185" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">L1/E1/B1C</text>

          <!-- E5b/B2b: 1207.14 -->
          <!-- x = 40 + (1207.14-1100)/600*600 = 40+107.14 = ~147 -->
          <rect x="140" y="80" width="14" height="24" rx="2" fill="var(--accent2)" opacity="0.7"/>
          <line x1="147" y1="80" x2="147" y2="58" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="0.8" opacity="0.6"/>
          <text x="147" y="52" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--mono)">1207</text>
          <text x="147" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">E5b/B2b</text>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="signal-structure">Signal structure</h2>
      <p>
        A GNSS signal is not a simple sine wave — it is a carefully composed combination of three components
        modulated together onto a carrier frequency:
      </p>

      <div class="signal-layers">
        <div class="signal-layer layer-carrier">
          <div class="layer-name">Carrier wave</div>
          <div class="layer-freq">e.g. 1575.42 MHz (GPS L1)</div>
          <div class="layer-desc">The radio frequency sine wave that carries everything else. Not directly useful for ranging — used for carrier phase measurements.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="signal-layer layer-code">
          <div class="layer-name">Ranging code (PRN code)</div>
          <div class="layer-freq">1.023 Mcps (GPS C/A) — 10.23 Mcps (P code)</div>
          <div class="layer-desc">A pseudo-random noise sequence modulated onto the carrier. Used by the receiver to measure signal travel time and compute the pseudorange.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="signal-layer layer-nav">
          <div class="layer-name">Navigation message</div>
          <div class="layer-freq">25–500 bps depending on signal type</div>
          <div class="layer-desc">Low-rate data broadcast containing satellite ephemeris (orbital parameters), clock corrections, ionospheric model and health status.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The modulation technique used is <strong>Binary Phase Shift Keying (BPSK)</strong> — the carrier
        phase is shifted by 180° to represent a 0 or 1 in the ranging code. More modern signals (GPS L1C,
        Galileo E1, BeiDou B1C) use <strong>Binary Offset Carrier (BOC)</strong> modulation which provides
        a sharper correlation peak and better multipath rejection.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="spreading-codes">Spreading codes — the ranging mechanism</h2>
      <p>
        The ranging code is the key to how GNSS measures distance. Each satellite broadcasts a unique
        <strong>Pseudo-Random Noise (PRN) code</strong> — a sequence that looks random but is completely
        deterministic and known to the receiver in advance.
      </p>
      <p>
        The GPS C/A (Coarse/Acquisition) code is 1,023 chips long at a rate of 1.023 million chips per
        second (Mcps), giving a period of exactly <strong>1 millisecond</strong>. The receiver generates
        an identical copy of the code and shifts it in time until it aligns with the received signal
        (maximum cross-correlation). The required time shift equals the signal propagation delay.
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">chip length = c / chip_rate = 299,792,458 / 1,023,000 ≈ 293 m</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          Each chip in the GPS C/A code corresponds to ~293 m of range. A receiver can measure the
          code phase to ~1% of a chip, giving code-based ranging accuracy of approximately <strong>3 m</strong>.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Why pseudo-random?</strong> PRN codes have near-zero cross-correlation between different
          satellites' codes. This means a receiver can separate signals from 30+ satellites all broadcasting
          on the same frequency simultaneously — each satellite is identified by its unique code. This is
          the fundamental trick that makes GNSS work.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>GPS ranging codes</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Code</th>
              <th>Rate</th>
              <th>Length</th>
              <th>Period</th>
              <th>Range noise (1σ)</th>
              <th>Access</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>C/A code</strong></td>
              <td>1.023 Mcps</td>
              <td>1,023 chips</td>
              <td>1 ms</td>
              <td>~3 m</td>
              <td>Open (all users)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>P(Y) code</strong></td>
              <td>10.23 Mcps</td>
              <td>6.19 × 10¹² chips</td>
              <td>7 days</td>
              <td>~0.3 m</td>
              <td>Encrypted (military)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>L1C</strong></td>
              <td>1.023 Mcps</td>
              <td>10,230 chips</td>
              <td>10 ms</td>
              <td>~1 m</td>
              <td>Open (Block III+)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>L2C</strong></td>
              <td>511.5 kcps</td>
              <td>767,250 chips</td>
              <td>1.5 s</td>
              <td>~3 m</td>
              <td>Open (Block IIR-M+)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>L5</strong></td>
              <td>10.23 Mcps</td>
              <td>10,230 chips</td>
              <td>1 ms</td>
              <td>~0.3 m</td>
              <td>Open (Block IIF+)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="cdma-fdma">CDMA vs FDMA</h2>
      <p>
        There are two fundamentally different approaches to distinguishing satellite signals:
      </p>

      <div class="compare-grid">
        <div class="compare-card">
          <div class="compare-header cdma-header">CDMA — Code Division Multiple Access</div>
          <div class="compare-body">
            <p>All satellites transmit on the <strong>same frequency</strong>. Each satellite is identified
            by its unique PRN code. The receiver uses code correlation to separate signals.</p>
            <p><strong>Used by:</strong> GPS, Galileo, BeiDou, and the new GLONASS CDMA signals (L3)</p>
            <div class="compare-pros">
              <div class="compare-pro">✓ Simpler receiver hardware</div>
              <div class="compare-pro">✓ Enables interoperability (GPS L1 = Galileo E1 = BeiDou B1C at 1575.42 MHz)</div>
              <div class="compare-pro">✓ More robust to interference</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-card">
          <div class="compare-header fdma-header">FDMA — Frequency Division Multiple Access</div>
          <div class="compare-body">
            <p>Each satellite transmits on a <strong>slightly different frequency</strong>. Signals are
            separated by filtering in the frequency domain.</p>
            <p><strong>Used by:</strong> Legacy GLONASS (L1, L2). Each satellite occupies a channel
            spaced 562.5 kHz apart.</p>
            <div class="compare-pros">
              <div class="compare-pro">✓ Natural resistance to broadband jamming</div>
              <div class="compare-pro">✓ No near-far problem (code orthogonality not required)</div>
              <div class="compare-con">✗ Requires wider receiver bandwidth</div>
              <div class="compare-con">✗ Inter-channel biases complicate RTK processing</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔧</div>
        <div>
          <strong>For RTK engineers:</strong> GLONASS FDMA signals introduce inter-channel biases (ICBs)
          in the carrier phase that are receiver-type dependent. An RTK baseline between two different
          receiver types (e.g. Trimble and NovAtel) will have residual GLONASS phase biases that must
          be calibrated or the GLONASS satellites excluded from the ambiguity resolution process.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="carrier-phase">Carrier phase — the precision measurement</h2>
      <p>
        Code-based ranging gives ~3 m accuracy. Carrier phase measurement gives ~3 mm accuracy.
        The difference is enormous — and it comes from measuring the phase of the carrier wave itself,
        not just the code.
      </p>
      <p>
        The GPS L1 carrier has a wavelength of:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">λ = c / f = 299,792,458 / 1,575,420,000 ≈ 0.1903 m (19.03 cm)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          A receiver can measure the phase of this 19 cm wave to about 1% — roughly <strong>2 mm</strong>.
          This is the source of RTK accuracy.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The carrier phase observation Φ from satellite <em>i</em> to receiver <em>r</em> is:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">Φ<sub>r</sub><sup>i</sup> = ρ<sub>r</sub><sup>i</sup>/λ + N<sub>r</sub><sup>i</sup> − f·δt<sub>r</sub> + f·δt<sup>i</sup> − I<sub>r</sub><sup>i</sup>/λ + T<sub>r</sub><sup>i</sup>/λ + ε</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          where ρ = geometric range, N = integer ambiguity (unknown number of whole cycles),
          δt<sub>r</sub> = receiver clock error, δt<sup>i</sup> = satellite clock error,
          I = ionospheric delay, T = tropospheric delay, ε = noise.
          The critical unknown is <strong>N — the integer ambiguity</strong>.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The problem with carrier phase is the <strong>integer ambiguity N</strong>. When the receiver
        first locks onto the signal, it can measure the fractional phase (less than one cycle) but does
        not know how many complete wavelengths lie between satellite and receiver. Resolving N to its
        correct integer value is the central challenge of RTK — covered in depth in the
        <a href="/learn/positioning/rtk">RTK article</a>.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="dual-frequency">Why dual-frequency matters</h2>
      <p>
        The ionosphere — a layer of plasma 50–1000 km above Earth — delays GNSS signals by an amount
        that depends on the signal frequency. Specifically, the ionospheric delay is proportional to
        1/f²:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">I = 40.3 × TEC / f²</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          where TEC is Total Electron Content in TECU (electrons/m²) and f is frequency in Hz.
          A typical TEC of 10 TECU causes ~0.16 m delay on L1 (1575.42 MHz) and ~0.27 m on L2 (1227.60 MHz).
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Because the delay is frequency-dependent, a receiver measuring on <em>two</em> frequencies can
        form the <strong>ionosphere-free linear combination</strong> that eliminates the first-order
        ionospheric effect entirely:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">ρ<sub>IF</sub> = (f₁² · ρ₁ − f₂² · ρ₂) / (f₁² − f₂²)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          For GPS L1/L2: f₁ = 1575.42 MHz, f₂ = 1227.60 MHz.
          The ionosphere-free pseudorange ρ<sub>IF</sub> has the first-order ionospheric delay removed.
          This is why dual-frequency receivers achieve significantly better accuracy in high-ionosphere conditions.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">📡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Galileo advantage:</strong> Galileo E1 (1575.42 MHz) and E5a (1176.45 MHz) are
          fully interoperable with GPS L1 and L5. A dual-frequency GPS+Galileo receiver can form
          the ionosphere-free combination using signals from <em>both</em> constellations,
          giving significantly more satellites to work with and better geometry.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📻</div>
          <div class="summary-title">L-band choice</div>
          <div class="summary-body">1–2 GHz passes through the ionosphere, allows compact antennas and is internationally protected for satellite navigation.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔢</div>
          <div class="summary-title">PRN codes enable ranging</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Each satellite's unique pseudo-random code allows simultaneous multi-satellite tracking on the same frequency (CDMA). Code correlation gives ~3 m ranging accuracy.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">〰️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Carrier phase for precision</div>
          <div class="summary-body">The 19 cm carrier wavelength can be measured to ~2 mm — but only after solving the integer ambiguity N. This is the basis of RTK and PPP.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">2️⃣</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Dual-frequency eliminates iono</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Ionospheric delay is proportional to 1/f². Two frequencies allow the delay to be computed and removed — no correction service needed.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/fundamentals/how-gnss-works" class="nav-prev">← How GNSS Works</a>
        <a href="/learn/fundamentals/error-sources" class="nav-next">Error Sources →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>IS-GPS-200N — GPS Interface Specification. <a href="https://www.navcen.uscg.gov/sites/default/files/pdf/gps/IS-GPS-200N.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NAVCEN →</a></li>
          <li>Kaplan, E. D. & Hegarty, C. J. (2017). <em>Understanding GPS/GNSS: Principles and Applications</em>, 3rd ed. Artech House. Chapter 4.</li>
          <li>Galileo OS SIS ICD. <a href="https://www.gsc-europa.eu/sites/default/files/sites/all/files/Galileo-OS-SIS-ICD.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GSC Europa →</a></li>
          <li>Betz, J. W. (2016). <em>Engineering Satellite-Based Navigation and Timing</em>. Wiley-IEEE Press.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

